<glossary>
<definition id="fs-idm57603984">
<term>alpha particle</term>
<meaning id="fs-idp24947504"><emphasis effect="bold">(α</emphasis> or <m:math><m:msubsup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mn mathvariant="bold">2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mn mathvariant="bold">4</m:mn></m:msubsup><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">He</m:mtext></m:math> or <m:math><m:msubsup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mn mathvariant="bold">2</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mn mathvariant="bold">4</m:mn></m:msubsup><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">α</m:mtext><m:mo>)</m:mo></m:math> high-energy helium nucleus; a helium atom that has lost two electrons and contains two protons and two neutrons</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-idm54113552">
<term>antimatter</term>
<meaning id="fs-idp37734928">particles with the same mass but opposite properties (such as charge) of ordinary particles</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-idp335278976">
<term>beta particle</term>
<meaning id="fs-idp158236128"><m:math><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">(β</m:mtext></m:math> or <m:math><m:msubsup><m:mrow/><m:mn mathvariant="bold">−1</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.5em"/><m:mn mathvariant="bold">0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msubsup><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">e</m:mtext></m:math> or <m:math><m:msubsup><m:mrow/><m:mn mathvariant="bold">−1</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.5em"/><m:mn mathvariant="bold">0</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msubsup><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">β</m:mtext><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">)</m:mtext></m:math> high-energy electron</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-idm12021616">
<term>gamma ray</term>
<meaning id="fs-idp6179648"><emphasis effect="bold">(γ</emphasis> or <m:math><m:msubsup><m:mrow/><m:mrow><m:mn mathvariant="bold">0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mn mathvariant="bold">0</m:mn></m:msubsup><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">γ</m:mtext><m:mtext mathvariant="bold">)</m:mtext></m:math> short wavelength, high-energy electromagnetic radiation that exhibits wave-particle duality</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-idm45950256">
<term>nuclear reaction</term>
<meaning id="fs-idm18218400">change to a nucleus resulting in changes in the atomic number, mass number, or energy state</meaning>
</definition>
<definition id="fs-idp72108384">
